{"key":"processedPost-11512759","value":{"id":11512759,"first":11512339,"last":11520144,"when":1259020444,"utime":"11/24/09 01:54 AM","content":"Get some petri dishes.&nbsp; I've yet to see anyone do a successful strain isolation on agar using jars.&nbsp; Petri dishes are ten to fifteen cents each, and jars are nearly a dollar each.&nbsp; Use jars for grains or brf and petri dishes for agar.&nbsp; You're going to need a few dozen to get started, and the jars use up a lot of real estate.&nbsp; In addition, the CO2 builds up in the bottom of the jar, choking the mycelium.&nbsp; Petri dishes are shallow and this problem doesn't occur.&nbsp; <br /><br />Using jars instead of petri dishes is like using a pair of pliers to drive in a nail instead of a hammer.<br />RR","title":"Re: agar","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}